WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:07.594 --> 00:00:09.260
MARY GROVE: So good
afternoon, everyone.

00:00:09.260 --> 00:00:11.640
Are we having a
great day so far?

00:00:11.640 --> 00:00:12.430
Wonderful.

00:00:12.430 --> 00:00:13.580
Wonderful.

00:00:13.580 --> 00:00:16.360
Well, I am so honored to host a
discussion today with a leader

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:19.440
I very much admire,
someone who really

00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:21.860
is a leader in both the
finance and tech worlds

00:00:21.860 --> 00:00:24.550
and is able to brilliantly
bridge between the two.

00:00:24.550 --> 00:00:28.020
As Karishma mentioned, Ruth is
Senior Vice President and Chief

00:00:28.020 --> 00:00:31.530
Financial Officer of Alphabet,
and she joined the company

00:00:31.530 --> 00:00:33.630
in May 2015.

00:00:33.630 --> 00:00:36.830
Prior to that, Ruth was
Executive Vice President

00:00:36.830 --> 00:00:40.050
and Chief Financial Officer of
Morgan Stanley, where she also

00:00:40.050 --> 00:00:41.810
held a variety of
leadership roles

00:00:41.810 --> 00:00:45.310
prior to joining the highest
ranks of the company.

00:00:45.310 --> 00:00:48.920
Ruth has an amazing,
diverse set of interests.

00:00:48.920 --> 00:00:51.280
She is the Vice Chair of
the Stanford University

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:52.840
Board of Trustees.

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:54.680
She is also on the
Board of Directors

00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:57.090
of the Council for
Foreign Relations.

00:00:57.090 --> 00:01:01.120
She holds an undergrad degree
from Stanford University, MBA

00:01:01.120 --> 00:01:03.560
from the Wharton
School, and a master's

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:05.570
from the London
School of Economics.

00:01:05.570 --> 00:01:08.590
So Ruth is someone who really
has been transformative in sort

00:01:08.590 --> 00:01:11.375
of shaping the next
chapter of our company,

00:01:11.375 --> 00:01:12.750
and we are so
honored to have her

00:01:12.750 --> 00:01:15.020
here today to share some
personal insights with us as

00:01:15.020 --> 00:01:15.520
well.

00:01:15.520 --> 00:01:16.490
So welcome, Ruth.

00:01:16.490 --> 00:01:16.754
RUTH PORAT: Thank you.

00:01:16.754 --> 00:01:18.254
It's great to be
here with everyone.

00:01:18.254 --> 00:01:18.823
Thank you.

00:01:18.823 --> 00:01:22.610
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:22.610 --> 00:01:25.690
MARY GROVE: So Ruth, you
joined Alphabet, then Google,

00:01:25.690 --> 00:01:29.110
last May, and it's been quite
a ride the last 10 months.

00:01:29.110 --> 00:01:30.870
Can you tell me about
your current focus

00:01:30.870 --> 00:01:33.937
areas and sort of what are your
highest priorities right now?

00:01:33.937 --> 00:01:35.520
RUTH PORAT: Well,
the biggest surprise

00:01:35.520 --> 00:01:38.140
when I joined Google
at the time-- Alphabet

00:01:38.140 --> 00:01:40.817
now-- is how early
stage Google really is.

00:01:40.817 --> 00:01:42.650
And when you think about
all of the products

00:01:42.650 --> 00:01:45.070
we have, just go through
them one after the other,

00:01:45.070 --> 00:01:47.000
it's clear how
early stage we are,

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:49.980
which is extraordinary to say
with a company of our scale.

00:01:49.980 --> 00:01:52.826
So you think about how many
people still are not online.

00:01:52.826 --> 00:01:54.950
They're going to go online
with the mobile handset.

00:01:54.950 --> 00:01:56.870
You think about how
we're using our phones.

00:01:56.870 --> 00:02:00.675
You think about advertising
moving from offline to online,

00:02:00.675 --> 00:02:02.300
and what that means
for YouTube, or you

00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:05.210
think about companies
moving to the cloud.

00:02:05.210 --> 00:02:08.050
And the fact that
we're really early

00:02:08.050 --> 00:02:10.389
means that we have a
ton of opportunities.

00:02:10.389 --> 00:02:13.980
And the biggest challenge last
year was the 2016 budgeting.

00:02:13.980 --> 00:02:15.090
How do you prioritize?

00:02:15.090 --> 00:02:18.190
How do I determine, working
with business leaders,

00:02:18.190 --> 00:02:21.070
where to put funding,
how to allocate capital?

00:02:21.070 --> 00:02:24.660
And it was a tough process,
a really productive process.

00:02:24.660 --> 00:02:26.410
But it's also not a
once-and-done process.

00:02:26.410 --> 00:02:29.510
So as we completed the
year, we set a number

00:02:29.510 --> 00:02:31.460
of milestones,
business and technical,

00:02:31.460 --> 00:02:34.577
for business leaders as we
think about how to fund.

00:02:34.577 --> 00:02:35.910
And we're still working on that.

00:02:35.910 --> 00:02:37.571
And I think it's
really a testament

00:02:37.571 --> 00:02:39.820
to just how many extraordinary
opportunities are still

00:02:39.820 --> 00:02:40.640
out there.

00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:42.010
MARY GROVE: So much to
accomplish, come in,

00:02:42.010 --> 00:02:44.090
wrap your head around it,
and then go immediately

00:02:44.090 --> 00:02:45.310
into annual planning.

00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:47.170
So well done.

00:02:47.170 --> 00:02:50.440
So you were a seasoned
executive at Wall Street.

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:52.830
How has the transition
been to Silicon Valley?

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:54.840
And can you sort of
compare the culture

00:02:54.840 --> 00:02:57.980
of Wall Street to
Silicon Valley?

00:02:57.980 --> 00:03:00.570
RUTH PORAT: It's probably
more similar for me

00:03:00.570 --> 00:03:02.710
than I think many would expect.

00:03:02.710 --> 00:03:03.859
I grew up out here.

00:03:03.859 --> 00:03:06.400
I went to high school just down
the street at Menlo-Atherton.

00:03:06.400 --> 00:03:07.150
I went to Stanford.

00:03:07.150 --> 00:03:08.774
As you said, I'm on
the Stanford board,

00:03:08.774 --> 00:03:11.800
so I had been out here all
the time for the board.

00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:15.520
And every time I came out here,
I left, I got back to New York,

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:18.040
and said, the optimism
in Silicon Valley

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:21.420
is extraordinary, and it's
what makes this country great.

00:03:21.420 --> 00:03:24.430
And when I came
back out here, that

00:03:24.430 --> 00:03:26.180
was the most
embracing part of it.

00:03:26.180 --> 00:03:29.380
But I think the reason
it's not that different

00:03:29.380 --> 00:03:32.361
in certain respects is what
kept me at Morgan Stanley

00:03:32.361 --> 00:03:34.610
much longer than I anticipated--
I used to always tell

00:03:34.610 --> 00:03:36.830
my family, I'm going to be at
Morgan Stanley for five years

00:03:36.830 --> 00:03:38.246
and then I'm moving
back out here.

00:03:38.246 --> 00:03:40.480
And after 28 years, they
thought I couldn't count.

00:03:40.480 --> 00:03:42.990
But the reason I
stayed was I was

00:03:42.990 --> 00:03:45.250
solving clients' problems,
working with the greatest

00:03:45.250 --> 00:03:45.750
clients.

00:03:45.750 --> 00:03:47.990
Got to work with
Google on the IPO.

00:03:47.990 --> 00:03:50.310
But it was a constant
learning experience,

00:03:50.310 --> 00:03:52.590
and there were new things
to address all the time.

00:03:52.590 --> 00:03:54.490
New industries were created.

00:03:54.490 --> 00:03:56.820
And it's that learning
element that I

00:03:56.820 --> 00:03:59.430
find so invigorating
about being out here.

00:03:59.430 --> 00:04:00.460
MARY GROVE: So 28 years.

00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:02.320
That was a huge chapter.

00:04:02.320 --> 00:04:04.360
Now it's been 10
months to look at.

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:06.770
What has been your proudest
accomplishment of the last 10

00:04:06.770 --> 00:04:09.439
months since joining Alphabet?

00:04:09.439 --> 00:04:11.230
RUTH PORAT: This may
sound like an odd one,

00:04:11.230 --> 00:04:14.560
but I think culture is so
critical to the success

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:17.100
of any organization.

00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:20.870
Culture defines the way people
act in ways that rules can't.

00:04:20.870 --> 00:04:23.240
It's just the
unwritten, the ethics,

00:04:23.240 --> 00:04:24.860
the creed that people follow.

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:27.630
And I feel very
much at home here.

00:04:27.630 --> 00:04:30.040
I feel I've got an
extraordinary team.

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:33.430
And for me, just being able to
get in the slipstream is what

00:04:33.430 --> 00:04:35.720
it feels like, is really
important to being

00:04:35.720 --> 00:04:37.860
able to get things done.

00:04:37.860 --> 00:04:40.280
MARY GROVE: So looking
across the Google universe,

00:04:40.280 --> 00:04:42.870
then, what is a product area
or an emerging technology

00:04:42.870 --> 00:04:47.815
that you're especially bullish
on, excited about, and why?

00:04:47.815 --> 00:04:50.190
RUTH PORAT: It's a hard one
to answer, because as I said,

00:04:50.190 --> 00:04:52.850
we're so early stage
across a number of areas.

00:04:52.850 --> 00:04:57.050
I'm really excited about the way
the personal assistant machine

00:04:57.050 --> 00:04:59.800
learning is affecting how we
use our phone, the ability

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:03.747
to predict what we need
and be so much more useful.

00:05:03.747 --> 00:05:05.580
I love what's going on
with virtual reality.

00:05:05.580 --> 00:05:08.680
I'm really excited about what
we're doing in education.

00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:13.240
We are a leading player in
schools with our Chromebooks.

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:17.337
And more than that, we have
this virtual reality product

00:05:17.337 --> 00:05:19.170
called Cardboard, which
hopefully all of you

00:05:19.170 --> 00:05:20.380
have experienced.

00:05:20.380 --> 00:05:23.130
And we can take
kids back in history

00:05:23.130 --> 00:05:26.980
and around the globe with
something that's super simple.

00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:29.290
You just slot your phone
in, and it's the ability

00:05:29.290 --> 00:05:31.380
to provide anybody--
it's not just

00:05:31.380 --> 00:05:34.550
for the few elite-- anybody can
go anywhere around the globe.

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:38.340
And the ability to tell kids,
you can be anything, you

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:39.520
can get anywhere.

00:05:39.520 --> 00:05:40.790
I find that really exciting.

00:05:40.790 --> 00:05:45.710
So it's not a very fair answer,
but it's an accurate answer.

00:05:45.710 --> 00:05:48.600
We have a leader who's
focused on something

00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:51.080
that's a priority for us,
the next billion users.

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:54.400
The ability to bring the next
four to five billion people out

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:57.890
of poverty by giving them
access to information.

00:05:57.890 --> 00:06:00.120
All of these things
to me are what makes

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:01.539
it so exciting to be here.

00:06:01.539 --> 00:06:03.580
MARY GROVE: It's so amazing
and refreshing for me

00:06:03.580 --> 00:06:05.996
to hear you say that Google's
early stage in so many ways,

00:06:05.996 --> 00:06:09.680
because I joined Google
in 2004, so 12 years ago,

00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:12.220
and at the time we were
about 2,000 people.

00:06:12.220 --> 00:06:14.210
Now, of course, we're
over 60,000 people.

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:16.700
But refreshing for
me and so many of us

00:06:16.700 --> 00:06:19.030
to still remember that we
still are so early stage

00:06:19.030 --> 00:06:22.627
in so many areas, and there's so
much opportunity still to come.

00:06:22.627 --> 00:06:23.460
RUTH PORAT: Exactly.

00:06:23.460 --> 00:06:25.300
MARY GROVE: So I want
to shift gears a bit

00:06:25.300 --> 00:06:28.025
and talk about leadership,
and your perspective on that,

00:06:28.025 --> 00:06:30.240
and lessons that we
can learn from you.

00:06:30.240 --> 00:06:32.450
So what would you say
you look for most?

00:06:32.450 --> 00:06:34.950
What core attributes,
when you build a team

00:06:34.950 --> 00:06:37.320
and you hire leadership
into your team,

00:06:37.320 --> 00:06:38.951
what do you look for?

00:06:38.951 --> 00:06:40.700
RUTH PORAT: I look for
a number of things.

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:43.200
One, clearly passion
and excellence

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:46.270
in all that's being done.

00:06:46.270 --> 00:06:47.900
I look for
intellectual curiosity,

00:06:47.900 --> 00:06:50.360
because the one thing you know
is the world will constantly

00:06:50.360 --> 00:06:50.740
change.

00:06:50.740 --> 00:06:52.031
I want people who are learners.

00:06:52.031 --> 00:06:54.880
I want people who always
start questions with, well,

00:06:54.880 --> 00:06:55.890
what are we solving for?

00:06:55.890 --> 00:06:58.570
Because you can solve
any problem if you stop

00:06:58.570 --> 00:07:03.880
and actually ask, how do we
think about this differently?

00:07:03.880 --> 00:07:07.300
I do like to have
a mix of people

00:07:07.300 --> 00:07:09.770
for whom a role is
a massive stretch

00:07:09.770 --> 00:07:13.880
goal, coupled with those where
they have pattern recognition.

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:15.250
That's a term I use a lot.

00:07:15.250 --> 00:07:19.030
I think experience, and
therefore pattern recognition,

00:07:19.030 --> 00:07:20.830
is really valuable.

00:07:20.830 --> 00:07:23.630
And having the right
mix on your team is key,

00:07:23.630 --> 00:07:27.110
and it underscores why the
experience everyone gets

00:07:27.110 --> 00:07:29.735
in their first role or
second role is so key.

00:07:29.735 --> 00:07:31.720
You get a lot of
great experiences

00:07:31.720 --> 00:07:33.940
that then are relevant
in later life.

00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:37.550
I look for pattern recognition
as well as battle scars.

00:07:37.550 --> 00:07:40.332
And that's a term I ask
about in interviews.

00:07:40.332 --> 00:07:41.790
And then finally,
I think one thing

00:07:41.790 --> 00:07:45.840
that's absolutely critical for
a leadership team is diversity.

00:07:45.840 --> 00:07:47.600
There's a lot of
research that says

00:07:47.600 --> 00:07:51.276
that you have a better financial
outcome, a better business

00:07:51.276 --> 00:07:53.650
outcome when you have a diverse
team, because people come

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:55.560
with different
perspectives, and so I think

00:07:55.560 --> 00:07:58.200
all of those elements are
key to the way I think

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:00.110
about constructing the team.

00:08:00.110 --> 00:08:02.780
MARY GROVE: The diversity
point is very well-taken.

00:08:02.780 --> 00:08:04.620
I know that the
data does show us

00:08:04.620 --> 00:08:06.760
that it really is better
for business, not just

00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:08.040
the right thing to do.

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:10.300
And you've been
outspoken on this issue.

00:08:10.300 --> 00:08:14.510
Have you seen progress in the
industry over the past year?

00:08:14.510 --> 00:08:16.880
RUTH PORAT: A year is too
short a period of time.

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:17.950
It's a great question.

00:08:17.950 --> 00:08:19.890
I think what I've
seen a change--

00:08:19.890 --> 00:08:21.530
the change in the
last year is there

00:08:21.530 --> 00:08:23.710
is more discussion
about the fact

00:08:23.710 --> 00:08:26.300
that it's not just
the right thing to do,

00:08:26.300 --> 00:08:28.020
but it's right for business.

00:08:28.020 --> 00:08:32.590
And I think as we
collectively try and figure

00:08:32.590 --> 00:08:35.289
out how best to draw
men into the discussion,

00:08:35.289 --> 00:08:37.000
it's a really
valuable point, which

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.070
is, if you want to be
the strongest leader,

00:08:39.070 --> 00:08:40.330
you need a diverse team.

00:08:40.330 --> 00:08:42.121
You have to look at
the board of directors,

00:08:42.121 --> 00:08:44.580
your senior leadership
team, each of your teams.

00:08:44.580 --> 00:08:47.710
And so it's helpful as
we're trying to then come up

00:08:47.710 --> 00:08:50.230
with what are the concrete
steps that we can collectively

00:08:50.230 --> 00:08:51.750
take to make a difference?

00:08:51.750 --> 00:08:52.520
MARY GROVE: Right.

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:54.590
How many women in
this room have started

00:08:54.590 --> 00:08:56.420
a company, started
an organization,

00:08:56.420 --> 00:08:59.430
started their own venture?

00:08:59.430 --> 00:09:00.260
Great.

00:09:00.260 --> 00:09:03.017
So what advice, Ruth, do you
have for young founders who

00:09:03.017 --> 00:09:04.600
are just starting
out, especially when

00:09:04.600 --> 00:09:06.650
thinking about
building diverse teams?

00:09:06.650 --> 00:09:08.556
Often there's
discussion of, gosh,

00:09:08.556 --> 00:09:10.180
do you have to make
trade-offs in order

00:09:10.180 --> 00:09:11.240
to build a diverse team?

00:09:11.240 --> 00:09:14.240
And I emphatically think
that's not the case.

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:16.700
But how do you advise
leaders to think

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:18.840
about building an
organization with that in mind

00:09:18.840 --> 00:09:19.717
from the get go?

00:09:19.717 --> 00:09:22.050
RUTH PORAT: I think there are
two parts to your question

00:09:22.050 --> 00:09:23.890
which are really important.

00:09:23.890 --> 00:09:31.700
I think the first one is, how do
you build a super successful--

00:09:31.700 --> 00:09:33.120
how do you succeed?

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:34.790
If I start at kind
of the highest level

00:09:34.790 --> 00:09:36.720
and then go to the next
part of your question,

00:09:36.720 --> 00:09:39.000
which is diversity.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
I think it is critical
that each of us,

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.590
whether founding a
company, in a company,

00:09:44.590 --> 00:09:46.970
at every point in my career,
that we have sponsors.

00:09:46.970 --> 00:09:49.380
We have people who
will take risk on us.

00:09:49.380 --> 00:09:52.520
We will have people who are
in positions of authority

00:09:52.520 --> 00:09:55.170
and can give us those
breakaway opportunities.

00:09:55.170 --> 00:09:56.690
And in my career
I'm often asked,

00:09:56.690 --> 00:09:58.180
how did I know when
to move around?

00:09:58.180 --> 00:09:59.020
I didn't.

00:09:59.020 --> 00:10:02.880
I had somebody who was in
a position of authority who

00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:05.230
was willing to take
risk on me, who gave me

00:10:05.230 --> 00:10:06.850
the opportunity,
who said, I'm going

00:10:06.850 --> 00:10:09.500
to be your senior air cover.

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:12.290
One guy did that and
it was super valuable.

00:10:12.290 --> 00:10:14.602
Another one said, you're
going to sink or swim,

00:10:14.602 --> 00:10:16.060
and that's all
right because you're

00:10:16.060 --> 00:10:17.910
going to learn, no
matter what happens.

00:10:17.910 --> 00:10:19.390
And I'm there for you.

00:10:19.390 --> 00:10:21.430
And so to me, the
starting point is,

00:10:21.430 --> 00:10:23.680
make sure whether you're
starting a company

00:10:23.680 --> 00:10:25.610
or in a company, that
you have people there

00:10:25.610 --> 00:10:27.910
who have your back,
who have that pattern

00:10:27.910 --> 00:10:29.980
recognition, that
experience, who are

00:10:29.980 --> 00:10:31.860
taking a personal risk on you.

00:10:31.860 --> 00:10:34.580
That is the single most
important thing I can say.

00:10:34.580 --> 00:10:37.420
The first position I
had at Morgan Stanley,

00:10:37.420 --> 00:10:39.340
I worked for a guy on a deal.

00:10:39.340 --> 00:10:42.310
And I worked around
the clock and never

00:10:42.310 --> 00:10:44.020
even went to internal meetings.

00:10:44.020 --> 00:10:45.840
And about a month
or two into it,

00:10:45.840 --> 00:10:47.930
I finally got to go
to an internal meeting

00:10:47.930 --> 00:10:49.100
with the managing director.

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:51.200
And the managing director
looked at him and said,

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:53.430
is this the I that I
keep hearing about?

00:10:53.430 --> 00:10:54.710
And it was my wake-up moment.

00:10:54.710 --> 00:10:57.620
This guy had been taking
credit for my work.

00:10:57.620 --> 00:11:00.700
And what it really
taught me at an early age

00:11:00.700 --> 00:11:03.190
is, women in particular,
I think we have a tendency

00:11:03.190 --> 00:11:04.840
to put our head down,
work really hard,

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:06.652
and expect good
things will happen.

00:11:06.652 --> 00:11:08.360
And if you're working
for the wrong boss,

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:09.390
that's not going to happen.

00:11:09.390 --> 00:11:11.580
If you don't have people out
there who have your back,

00:11:11.580 --> 00:11:12.704
that's not going to happen.

00:11:12.704 --> 00:11:14.890
So the most
important message is,

00:11:14.890 --> 00:11:17.390
make sure you're working with
someone who has your back.

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:20.247
Make sure they're super
confident in themselves,

00:11:20.247 --> 00:11:22.580
because if they're not, it's
going to be harder for them

00:11:22.580 --> 00:11:24.080
to put themselves out there.

00:11:24.080 --> 00:11:27.970
Most-- not most, all of
my sponsors have been men.

00:11:27.970 --> 00:11:30.450
And the reason is,
as I was growing up

00:11:30.450 --> 00:11:32.110
through the
organization, there just

00:11:32.110 --> 00:11:34.990
weren't women in
senior positions.

00:11:34.990 --> 00:11:39.500
And so your sponsors don't
need to look like you to still

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:41.240
be in a position to help you.

00:11:41.240 --> 00:11:43.830
And so I think those
are critical elements.

00:11:43.830 --> 00:11:47.450
And then your other point, which
is so important, diversity.

00:11:47.450 --> 00:11:48.980
I agree with you.

00:11:48.980 --> 00:11:50.760
It's not a trade-off.

00:11:50.760 --> 00:11:54.710
We can look for the best
talent and round out our team.

00:11:54.710 --> 00:11:58.190
And I think that notion that you
can have tunnel vision if you

00:11:58.190 --> 00:12:01.280
don't have diversity
by gender, by race,

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:03.860
by socioeconomic background,
by sexual orientation--

00:12:03.860 --> 00:12:06.580
there are lot of different
ways we can bring diversity

00:12:06.580 --> 00:12:09.370
into your decision-making
team, and it's really important

00:12:09.370 --> 00:12:10.339
to do that.

00:12:10.339 --> 00:12:11.880
MARY GROVE: So to
your earlier point,

00:12:11.880 --> 00:12:14.080
the first point about
sponsors-- and you and I

00:12:14.080 --> 00:12:16.760
have spoken before about
how the process of getting

00:12:16.760 --> 00:12:19.480
a sponsor, which is different
from a mentor-- both

00:12:19.480 --> 00:12:21.361
are important-- is
somewhat organic.

00:12:21.361 --> 00:12:23.110
You don't just walk
up to someone and say,

00:12:23.110 --> 00:12:24.490
will you be my sponsor?

00:12:24.490 --> 00:12:26.900
So I thought you've
had really great advice

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:29.270
about how to
advocate for yourself

00:12:29.270 --> 00:12:31.340
and how to provide updates.

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:33.862
Can you elaborate a bit
on that for our audience?

00:12:33.862 --> 00:12:35.320
RUTH PORAT: I will,
but I think you

00:12:35.320 --> 00:12:36.570
made a really important point.

00:12:36.570 --> 00:12:38.370
I think some people
struggle with,

00:12:38.370 --> 00:12:40.100
can you just walk up
to somebody and say,

00:12:40.100 --> 00:12:41.780
will you be my sponsor?

00:12:41.780 --> 00:12:43.580
And the reason I
completely agree

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:47.810
with you is, your sponsor
is taking risk on you.

00:12:47.810 --> 00:12:49.800
And so they need to
know who you are.

00:12:49.800 --> 00:12:51.960
You need to have earned
the opportunity for them

00:12:51.960 --> 00:12:54.130
to actually put
themselves in a position

00:12:54.130 --> 00:12:55.610
where it could hurt
them personally

00:12:55.610 --> 00:12:58.120
or professionally if
you drop the ball.

00:12:58.120 --> 00:13:00.680
And so I completely
agree with you,

00:13:00.680 --> 00:13:02.620
you got to earn that right.

00:13:02.620 --> 00:13:05.540
I think there are a couple
of really important elements,

00:13:05.540 --> 00:13:07.270
in particular, for women.

00:13:07.270 --> 00:13:13.080
One is, too often, as I said, we
put our heads down, work hard,

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:16.820
and expect good things
will occur and be noticed.

00:13:16.820 --> 00:13:21.210
Men do a much
better job providing

00:13:21.210 --> 00:13:23.430
the head of a group,
the head of a business,

00:13:23.430 --> 00:13:26.390
with updates about what
they're doing than do women.

00:13:26.390 --> 00:13:29.970
And when I first was in a
position running a group,

00:13:29.970 --> 00:13:31.690
it really struck
me how often I'd

00:13:31.690 --> 00:13:35.410
get these really pithy, little
nice updates from the men.

00:13:35.410 --> 00:13:38.200
I just did this deal,
just had this win, just

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:39.410
accomplished whatever.

00:13:39.410 --> 00:13:41.190
And I wasn't getting
them from the women.

00:13:41.190 --> 00:13:43.064
And I went out and spoke
to a number of women

00:13:43.064 --> 00:13:44.980
and said, why aren't
you doing this?

00:13:44.980 --> 00:13:45.534
The guys are.

00:13:45.534 --> 00:13:47.700
And the answer was, well,
it seems really political.

00:13:47.700 --> 00:13:49.770
And my answer is,
it's not political.

00:13:49.770 --> 00:13:50.840
It's content.

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:54.579
And as a leader running
a large organization,

00:13:54.579 --> 00:13:56.870
I won't know what you're
doing if you don't talk about.

00:13:56.870 --> 00:13:57.370
It.

00:13:57.370 --> 00:13:58.610
So please let me know.

00:13:58.610 --> 00:14:00.610
Keep it pithy.

00:14:00.610 --> 00:14:03.530
And if it's uncomfortable
to talk about yourself, say,

00:14:03.530 --> 00:14:07.320
I want to highlight this great
thing that our team got done,

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:08.920
you know, my team
is extraordinary.

00:14:08.920 --> 00:14:12.220
So you can make it about the
team, which it usually is.

00:14:12.220 --> 00:14:14.160
So one is speaking up.

00:14:14.160 --> 00:14:17.280
There's an expression one
of my clients once used,

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:19.640
which is, the absence
of information

00:14:19.640 --> 00:14:20.980
is filled with dirt.

00:14:20.980 --> 00:14:23.072
And I use that
expression all the time.

00:14:23.072 --> 00:14:25.030
In fact, my kids are
tired of hearing about it,

00:14:25.030 --> 00:14:26.740
because if they're home
after midnight, I'll say,

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:28.460
the absence of information
is filled with dirt,

00:14:28.460 --> 00:14:30.610
so I assume they're obviously
dead on the side of a road,

00:14:30.610 --> 00:14:31.359
which they aren't.

00:14:31.359 --> 00:14:32.150
They're just out.

00:14:32.150 --> 00:14:34.070
But it's a really
important message,

00:14:34.070 --> 00:14:37.110
because if we don't communicate,
we don't say something,

00:14:37.110 --> 00:14:40.950
and the guys are, they're
filling it in and we are not.

00:14:40.950 --> 00:14:43.320
So make sure you communicate.

00:14:43.320 --> 00:14:45.120
Don't hold back.

00:14:45.120 --> 00:14:47.000
The second really
important one is

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.320
that when you're ready
for that next role,

00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:52.562
I think it's really
important to say something.

00:14:52.562 --> 00:14:54.770
And when you have a sponsor,
it makes it much easier.

00:14:54.770 --> 00:14:57.120
What I used to do
is say, you know,

00:14:57.120 --> 00:14:59.300
I'm kind of ready for
that next challenge.

00:14:59.300 --> 00:15:00.470
I love to learn.

00:15:00.470 --> 00:15:01.850
What's my highest and best use?

00:15:01.850 --> 00:15:03.780
I'm open for anything
whenever it comes up.

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:06.140
It wasn't like, I need
x and I need it now.

00:15:06.140 --> 00:15:09.850
It's what's my
highest and best use?

00:15:09.850 --> 00:15:13.840
And the other thing I've
found with women versus men

00:15:13.840 --> 00:15:17.190
is, I think we-- and
I will blame myself

00:15:17.190 --> 00:15:19.480
in early days-- you
kind of say it once

00:15:19.480 --> 00:15:21.930
and you think it's
registered, whereas men

00:15:21.930 --> 00:15:24.010
are really repetitive.

00:15:24.010 --> 00:15:25.940
It's like a war of attrition.

00:15:25.940 --> 00:15:29.700
Every single week, back at
you until you respond to it.

00:15:29.700 --> 00:15:35.106
And so what I'm telling men is,
if you hear a woman ask, think

00:15:35.106 --> 00:15:36.980
of it as like she's
screaming from a rooftop,

00:15:36.980 --> 00:15:38.438
and the next time
you hear, she may

00:15:38.438 --> 00:15:41.260
be leaving the organization,
whereas men will just

00:15:41.260 --> 00:15:42.830
do this war of attrition thing.

00:15:42.830 --> 00:15:45.590
But what I tell women is,
increase the frequency

00:15:45.590 --> 00:15:47.830
if you're ready for a
move, you're getting bored,

00:15:47.830 --> 00:15:50.050
don't get to the point where
you just kind of give up

00:15:50.050 --> 00:15:51.130
on where you are.

00:15:51.130 --> 00:15:51.885
Ask for it.

00:15:51.885 --> 00:15:54.246
I think that's another
really important element.

00:15:54.246 --> 00:15:56.620
MARY GROVE: I think that's
such insightful advice for all

00:15:56.620 --> 00:15:58.940
of us as women,
but also as women,

00:15:58.940 --> 00:16:01.870
when we reach leadership
roles or management positions,

00:16:01.870 --> 00:16:03.060
to keep an eye out for that.

00:16:03.060 --> 00:16:04.976
And if we're not getting
that type of feedback

00:16:04.976 --> 00:16:07.320
from the women on our team,
to go out and practically

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:09.790
seek it, and encourage
the frequent updates,

00:16:09.790 --> 00:16:10.900
the advocating.

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:12.941
RUTH PORAT: Well, that's
a really important point

00:16:12.941 --> 00:16:14.380
and it prompts another one.

00:16:14.380 --> 00:16:16.390
And data research
supports this one, too.

00:16:16.390 --> 00:16:18.070
Women tend to-- we
collectively tend

00:16:18.070 --> 00:16:20.270
to think we need to
have 100% of the skills

00:16:20.270 --> 00:16:23.490
before we're ready to say, I'm
ready for my next challenge,

00:16:23.490 --> 00:16:26.160
whereas men need 25%
to 50% of the skills

00:16:26.160 --> 00:16:27.790
and their hands
are up in the air.

00:16:27.790 --> 00:16:29.610
So your point's a
really important one.

00:16:29.610 --> 00:16:30.900
We may wait too long.

00:16:30.900 --> 00:16:33.850
And I think even
when we're asked,

00:16:33.850 --> 00:16:35.900
too often I find women
will say, I'm not ready.

00:16:35.900 --> 00:16:37.320
And my response has
been, well, then, you're

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:39.778
telling me that I'm an idiot
because I think you are ready.

00:16:39.778 --> 00:16:42.069
So let's have this
conversation one more time.

00:16:42.069 --> 00:16:44.110
So even when you think
you're not ready, you are.

00:16:44.110 --> 00:16:44.630
Think of it.

00:16:44.630 --> 00:16:47.440
The guys only need 25% to 50%.

00:16:47.440 --> 00:16:48.620
We're thinking we need 100%.

00:16:48.620 --> 00:16:49.850
There's a big gulf in there.

00:16:49.850 --> 00:16:53.349
So your point, I
completely agree with.

00:16:53.349 --> 00:16:55.140
MARY GROVE: I know a
lot of women at Google

00:16:55.140 --> 00:16:57.820
look at you in the most senior
level of leadership and think,

00:16:57.820 --> 00:16:58.930
that's so inspirational.

00:16:58.930 --> 00:17:00.380
Whether or not
I've ever met you,

00:17:00.380 --> 00:17:03.367
had a conversation with
you, I can look up to you.

00:17:03.367 --> 00:17:05.200
So you being in that
position of leadership,

00:17:05.200 --> 00:17:06.859
who do you look up to?

00:17:06.859 --> 00:17:10.839
Who are some of your main
influences and role models?

00:17:10.839 --> 00:17:13.339
RUTH PORAT: This is not supposed
to be a political statement

00:17:13.339 --> 00:17:15.319
because I've been answering
this question for a really

00:17:15.319 --> 00:17:16.990
long time, well
before the election,

00:17:16.990 --> 00:17:18.760
but-- just so you
know what I'm going.

00:17:21.960 --> 00:17:23.670
Hillary Clinton was
my senator, and I've

00:17:23.670 --> 00:17:25.670
been a supporter of hers
for a really long time.

00:17:25.670 --> 00:17:28.930
And when she became
secretary of state,

00:17:28.930 --> 00:17:30.750
she did something
that I've talked

00:17:30.750 --> 00:17:32.450
about in a different
context that I

00:17:32.450 --> 00:17:33.720
think is really important.

00:17:33.720 --> 00:17:35.660
To be identified
as a great leader,

00:17:35.660 --> 00:17:38.900
I think we each need to do
a brilliant job in our role.

00:17:38.900 --> 00:17:40.650
And I call that our sandbox.

00:17:40.650 --> 00:17:43.210
But then you need to go
outside of your sandbox

00:17:43.210 --> 00:17:45.860
and really push the frontier
and take on something bigger

00:17:45.860 --> 00:17:48.150
to actually make your
organization better

00:17:48.150 --> 00:17:49.351
as a result.

00:17:49.351 --> 00:17:50.850
And when she was
secretary of state,

00:17:50.850 --> 00:17:53.720
she had her day job, which
is a pretty big day job.

00:17:53.720 --> 00:17:56.340
And then she was also
focused on global women.

00:17:56.340 --> 00:17:59.150
And to me, if she could
be secretary of state

00:17:59.150 --> 00:18:01.800
and have this other
agenda, that's

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:04.580
exactly, in my view, what we
each need to be thinking about.

00:18:04.580 --> 00:18:07.270
How do we do what we do and
do it really brilliantly?

00:18:07.270 --> 00:18:08.860
And how do we make
the organization

00:18:08.860 --> 00:18:11.620
that we're part of better as
a result of us being there?

00:18:11.620 --> 00:18:15.590
So I would say she's the one.

00:18:15.590 --> 00:18:17.630
MARY GROVE: She's
an impressive woman.

00:18:17.630 --> 00:18:18.700
Absolutely.

00:18:18.700 --> 00:18:21.440
So prior to joining Google,
you were called Wall Street's

00:18:21.440 --> 00:18:22.880
most powerful woman.

00:18:22.880 --> 00:18:26.520
And I'm wondering, in
moments of great adversity,

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:29.620
great personal challenge, how
do you maintain your power,

00:18:29.620 --> 00:18:32.060
maintain your strength?

00:18:32.060 --> 00:18:34.870
RUTH PORAT: Well, I
think times of adversity

00:18:34.870 --> 00:18:38.440
are the greatest times to
learn, and to mobilize,

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:41.540
and to pull a team
together, and to have a win.

00:18:41.540 --> 00:18:46.610
And they're the most
poignant parts of my career.

00:18:46.610 --> 00:18:50.150
So I had the opportunity,
during the financial crisis,

00:18:50.150 --> 00:18:52.070
the secretary of the
treasury at the time,

00:18:52.070 --> 00:18:55.070
Hank Paulson, asked if I would
help lead a team to advise them

00:18:55.070 --> 00:18:58.210
what to do with the housing
market, Fannie Mae and Freddie

00:18:58.210 --> 00:19:00.830
Mac, a small $5
trillion industry.

00:19:00.830 --> 00:19:02.250
And then from
there we went right

00:19:02.250 --> 00:19:06.650
into the Lehman crisis weekend
and then the AIG weekend.

00:19:06.650 --> 00:19:09.030
AIG was the scariest
moment throughout

00:19:09.030 --> 00:19:10.100
the financial crisis.

00:19:10.100 --> 00:19:11.120
It was terrifying.

00:19:11.120 --> 00:19:12.610
And the reason it
was terrifying--

00:19:12.610 --> 00:19:14.100
and I am getting
to your question--

00:19:14.100 --> 00:19:15.516
the reason it was
terrifying is it

00:19:15.516 --> 00:19:18.342
felt like individuals and small
businesses would be wiped out

00:19:18.342 --> 00:19:19.550
and they never saw it coming.

00:19:19.550 --> 00:19:21.890
And I was sitting there
feeling like we really

00:19:21.890 --> 00:19:24.500
were in the midst
of what was going

00:19:24.500 --> 00:19:26.920
to be a horrendous meltdown.

00:19:26.920 --> 00:19:28.410
And so many people would suffer.

00:19:28.410 --> 00:19:30.660
It was the most
frightening moment.

00:19:30.660 --> 00:19:33.710
And beyond the, how
do you mobilize a team

00:19:33.710 --> 00:19:36.160
to problem solve,
which gets you focused,

00:19:36.160 --> 00:19:38.240
the other thing that
was really important

00:19:38.240 --> 00:19:42.570
is, I was thinking of my family,
and thinking, wow, everything's

00:19:42.570 --> 00:19:43.550
going to get wiped out.

00:19:43.550 --> 00:19:44.758
And I thought, you know what?

00:19:44.758 --> 00:19:47.690
We have our health I have
three amazing children.

00:19:47.690 --> 00:19:49.300
Been married for a
really long time.

00:19:49.300 --> 00:19:51.590
I don't have any regrets
about anything I've done.

00:19:51.590 --> 00:19:53.970
And I think that
question-- and I've

00:19:53.970 --> 00:19:56.910
framed it that way in the
past-- is don't have regrets.

00:19:56.910 --> 00:19:58.820
Don't put off your
life for another day.

00:19:58.820 --> 00:20:01.480
Don't put off for
this time when things

00:20:01.480 --> 00:20:04.070
are going to be fine, because
you just don't know what's

00:20:04.070 --> 00:20:05.890
going to happen along the way.

00:20:05.890 --> 00:20:08.390
So I think problem
solving is one part of it.

00:20:08.390 --> 00:20:12.420
And I actually think you learn
so much in times of adversity.

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:14.650
And don't forget to think
about how much you're

00:20:14.650 --> 00:20:16.106
learning and getting stronger.

00:20:16.106 --> 00:20:17.730
And then make sure,
though, that you've

00:20:17.730 --> 00:20:20.810
done everything in your life
that you want so that you don't

00:20:20.810 --> 00:20:23.570
question, well, why did I wait?

00:20:23.570 --> 00:20:24.820
MARY GROVE: Absolutely.

00:20:24.820 --> 00:20:27.400
So you talked about navigating
the financial crisis.

00:20:27.400 --> 00:20:30.690
Now your purview is looking
after the finances of Alphabet.

00:20:30.690 --> 00:20:32.050
No small task.

00:20:32.050 --> 00:20:35.100
So can you share with us a
couple, maybe, life hacks

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:37.760
for how you personally
prioritize your time

00:20:37.760 --> 00:20:40.224
and how you manage
your schedule?

00:20:40.224 --> 00:20:41.640
RUTH PORAT: That's
been a journey.

00:20:41.640 --> 00:20:46.060
I can tell you I have tried
a lot of different things.

00:20:46.060 --> 00:20:48.210
But there are two.

00:20:48.210 --> 00:20:50.560
First, I think
women-- at least I'll

00:20:50.560 --> 00:20:54.010
say for myself-- really
bad at saying no.

00:20:54.010 --> 00:20:58.520
And one of my--I actually have
it on my to do list-- say no.

00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:00.050
Because there are
a lot of really

00:21:00.050 --> 00:21:02.340
cool things that we get to do.

00:21:02.340 --> 00:21:04.177
And it's really easy,
and I love to learn.

00:21:04.177 --> 00:21:06.260
So it's like, well, I'll
do that and I'll do that.

00:21:06.260 --> 00:21:07.635
And then all of
a sudden you find

00:21:07.635 --> 00:21:10.130
you really don't have enough
time to live your life.

00:21:10.130 --> 00:21:12.817
And so that's one thing,
is having the discipline

00:21:12.817 --> 00:21:14.400
to make sure the bar
is high enough so

00:21:14.400 --> 00:21:17.310
that when you're doing something
you're not overextended.

00:21:17.310 --> 00:21:19.780
And I have found that to
be a learning experience.

00:21:19.780 --> 00:21:24.307
And the other is, start each
year with a set of priorities.

00:21:24.307 --> 00:21:26.890
For me, it's kind of, what are
the five things that are really

00:21:26.890 --> 00:21:28.490
important to get
accomplished where

00:21:28.490 --> 00:21:32.100
I can make a real
difference here at Alphabet?

00:21:32.100 --> 00:21:32.910
And keep them.

00:21:32.910 --> 00:21:34.180
They're on my to-do list.

00:21:34.180 --> 00:21:35.310
So I have a to-do list.

00:21:35.310 --> 00:21:38.800
It's got everybody I deal
with and the key things

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:40.080
I need to talk to them about.

00:21:40.080 --> 00:21:43.800
And I go through that every day,
and it's this constant process,

00:21:43.800 --> 00:21:46.070
so if I'm talking to you,
I'll pull out the things

00:21:46.070 --> 00:21:47.690
that we had dealt with before.

00:21:47.690 --> 00:21:50.840
But also on that are my
work priorities for the year

00:21:50.840 --> 00:21:52.760
and my family
priorities for the year.

00:21:52.760 --> 00:21:55.320
And I always look
back at those as well.

00:21:55.320 --> 00:21:56.840
And it keeps you
kind of grounded

00:21:56.840 --> 00:21:59.570
so that you don't end up getting
overextended, at least for me.

00:21:59.570 --> 00:22:00.610
MARY GROVE: All on
the same list, though,

00:22:00.610 --> 00:22:01.680
work and family together.

00:22:01.680 --> 00:22:06.140
So it's not this notion of
a work-life bifurcation,

00:22:06.140 --> 00:22:06.790
so to speak.

00:22:06.790 --> 00:22:08.045
RUTH PORAT: Well, my
first time I did it,

00:22:08.045 --> 00:22:10.320
I had the work stuff on the
left and the family stuff

00:22:10.320 --> 00:22:11.450
on the right.

00:22:11.450 --> 00:22:13.340
And it's sort of
evolved over time.

00:22:13.340 --> 00:22:15.330
But it's one integrated thing.

00:22:15.330 --> 00:22:17.454
MARY GROVE: So if you only
get to pick five things,

00:22:17.454 --> 00:22:18.790
how high level is each bucket?

00:22:18.790 --> 00:22:20.420
RUTH PORAT: They're
pretty high level.

00:22:20.420 --> 00:22:20.680
MARY GROVE: It's a lot.

00:22:20.680 --> 00:22:22.210
RUTH PORAT: There's a lot there.

00:22:22.210 --> 00:22:22.820
MARY GROVE: Absolutely.

00:22:22.820 --> 00:22:24.444
So I want to shift
gears a bit and talk

00:22:24.444 --> 00:22:26.994
a little bit about the
economic environment right now.

00:22:26.994 --> 00:22:29.410
As we've seen, we have a lot
of entrepreneurs in the room.

00:22:29.410 --> 00:22:32.842
So I want to ask you, do you
think that current startup

00:22:32.842 --> 00:22:34.800
valuations-- especially
here in Silicon Valley,

00:22:34.800 --> 00:22:37.640
there's been so much talk
and so much hype-- do

00:22:37.640 --> 00:22:39.840
you think that they
are A, reasonable,

00:22:39.840 --> 00:22:43.010
and are they sustainable?

00:22:43.010 --> 00:22:46.880
RUTH PORAT: If you go back over
the history of startups, what

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:50.210
you'll find-- and Mary
Meeker was the research

00:22:50.210 --> 00:22:52.910
analyst at Morgan Stanley when
I was running tech banking back

00:22:52.910 --> 00:22:56.440
in the '90s, and she used to
always make this point-- is

00:22:56.440 --> 00:22:59.090
something like 70% fail.

00:22:59.090 --> 00:23:00.380
70% of startups fail.

00:23:00.380 --> 00:23:03.000
90% of the value is created
by 10% of the companies.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:05.790
There's a really
high bar for success.

00:23:05.790 --> 00:23:06.960
It is hard.

00:23:06.960 --> 00:23:09.860
And I think the key lesson
I learned back in the '90s,

00:23:09.860 --> 00:23:14.470
in that bubble, was that a
lot of companies were started.

00:23:14.470 --> 00:23:17.170
But there really wasn't
anything that was truly

00:23:17.170 --> 00:23:18.740
differentiating about them.

00:23:18.740 --> 00:23:21.180
At the time, it was the
early days of the internet,

00:23:21.180 --> 00:23:23.000
and people thought that if
you're using the internet,

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:24.130
you're an internet company.

00:23:24.130 --> 00:23:26.650
But if you weren't doing
anything transformative,

00:23:26.650 --> 00:23:28.470
the internet, as we
subsequently learned,

00:23:28.470 --> 00:23:31.550
was like you launched a catalog.

00:23:31.550 --> 00:23:34.630
There was really nothing new
and differentiating about it.

00:23:34.630 --> 00:23:38.750
And the key thing that I spent
a lot of time on as a banker,

00:23:38.750 --> 00:23:41.560
is this a company or
is this a product?

00:23:41.560 --> 00:23:44.760
And so I think for
great companies,

00:23:44.760 --> 00:23:48.720
you're going to find there'll
be a lot of interest,

00:23:48.720 --> 00:23:51.670
and valuation can be
sustainable, in particular

00:23:51.670 --> 00:23:55.330
given how much larger the
market is today than it was.

00:23:55.330 --> 00:23:57.800
But you have to go back
to, in an environment where

00:23:57.800 --> 00:24:00.104
a lot of things can get
funded, do you actually

00:24:00.104 --> 00:24:01.520
have something
that's sustainable?

00:24:01.520 --> 00:24:05.670
And there are times where
there's a blurring of that.

00:24:05.670 --> 00:24:08.440
But the great companies
will transcend

00:24:08.440 --> 00:24:11.560
whatever these kind of peaks
and valleys are in markets.

00:24:11.560 --> 00:24:13.400
MARY GROVE: So what
are the primary lessons

00:24:13.400 --> 00:24:16.800
that we should all remember
from the bubble of 2000?

00:24:16.800 --> 00:24:19.510
And do you think we're
in a bubble today?

00:24:19.510 --> 00:24:22.340
RUTH PORAT: So the main
one from the bubble of 2000

00:24:22.340 --> 00:24:27.350
is that, do you have something
that is truly differentiated?

00:24:27.350 --> 00:24:28.104
Is it a product?

00:24:28.104 --> 00:24:28.770
Is it a company?

00:24:28.770 --> 00:24:31.720
What makes it so differentiated?

00:24:31.720 --> 00:24:35.320
And make sure you're
getting-- make

00:24:35.320 --> 00:24:37.620
sure you've got good people
around you who can provide

00:24:37.620 --> 00:24:40.210
some lateral vision,
who can give you

00:24:40.210 --> 00:24:42.090
the benefit of a
lot of the scars

00:24:42.090 --> 00:24:44.720
they've gotten going through a
whole host of experience, who

00:24:44.720 --> 00:24:46.640
will truly challenge you.

00:24:46.640 --> 00:24:50.020
I have often said, I like
people who are in my face,

00:24:50.020 --> 00:24:53.080
because none of us have a
monopoly on great ideas.

00:24:53.080 --> 00:24:55.220
And if somebody is
not challenging me,

00:24:55.220 --> 00:24:58.740
I'm not going to get
pushed as far as I would

00:24:58.740 --> 00:25:00.840
want if you want to succeed.

00:25:00.840 --> 00:25:03.740
So that's probably the
most important from 2000.

00:25:03.740 --> 00:25:05.560
There are a couple
that are really

00:25:05.560 --> 00:25:08.820
important from the crisis of
2008, the financial crisis.

00:25:08.820 --> 00:25:10.990
And I quote those
all the time as well.

00:25:10.990 --> 00:25:13.160
The first and
really important one

00:25:13.160 --> 00:25:16.720
is how important it is to
build a solid foundation

00:25:16.720 --> 00:25:18.930
for your company well
ahead of when you need it.

00:25:18.930 --> 00:25:21.340
Any great company, I
believe, in any industry

00:25:21.340 --> 00:25:22.644
will fail if you don't do that.

00:25:22.644 --> 00:25:24.060
And the metaphor
is, you would not

00:25:24.060 --> 00:25:27.190
drive a car at 100 miles an
hour with mud on the windshield

00:25:27.190 --> 00:25:28.920
because you can't see
where you're going.

00:25:28.920 --> 00:25:31.420
And if you haven't built a good
foundation for your company,

00:25:31.420 --> 00:25:33.490
you don't know when you're
about to hit a wall.

00:25:33.490 --> 00:25:36.330
And you really need to
invest in boring stuff

00:25:36.330 --> 00:25:38.760
like financial control
systems, risk management,

00:25:38.760 --> 00:25:40.980
those kinds of things
that give you visibility.

00:25:40.980 --> 00:25:43.130
That's one really
important lesson.

00:25:43.130 --> 00:25:44.690
And the other very
important lesson

00:25:44.690 --> 00:25:46.480
from the financial
crisis is something

00:25:46.480 --> 00:25:50.940
Hank Paulson said
to me, which was,

00:25:50.940 --> 00:25:54.140
you need to have the will and
the means to solve a problem.

00:25:54.140 --> 00:25:56.180
And too often, by the
time you have the will,

00:25:56.180 --> 00:25:57.830
you no longer have the means.

00:25:57.830 --> 00:25:59.320
And he was talking about Greece.

00:25:59.320 --> 00:26:03.310
There was no will to solve
Greece in the early days.

00:26:03.310 --> 00:26:04.960
We had the financial
means to do it,

00:26:04.960 --> 00:26:06.540
but we didn't have
the will to do it.

00:26:06.540 --> 00:26:10.640
And as a result, it spread to
Italy and Spain and Portugal.

00:26:10.640 --> 00:26:14.290
It became a contagion
across southern Europe.

00:26:14.290 --> 00:26:17.060
And his point, you have to
have the will and the means,

00:26:17.060 --> 00:26:19.350
why is that relevant
to your question?

00:26:19.350 --> 00:26:21.970
I think it is relevant because--
and it goes back to my answer

00:26:21.970 --> 00:26:24.200
to your first
question-- we at Google,

00:26:24.200 --> 00:26:26.960
at Alphabet, have $73 billion.

00:26:26.960 --> 00:26:28.660
We can do a whole
host of things.

00:26:28.660 --> 00:26:30.980
But if we don't
prioritize, we're

00:26:30.980 --> 00:26:35.090
going to spend a lot
of resources on things

00:26:35.090 --> 00:26:36.900
down on the bottom of the list.

00:26:36.900 --> 00:26:39.756
We're going to dissipate
the means, as opposed

00:26:39.756 --> 00:26:41.880
to putting all of our weight
behind the big things.

00:26:41.880 --> 00:26:46.110
And so prioritization, for all
of us, is really important.

00:26:46.110 --> 00:26:48.090
And I would say when you
don't have the means,

00:26:48.090 --> 00:26:50.200
it becomes even more important.

00:26:50.200 --> 00:26:51.850
So I think that there
are some lessons

00:26:51.850 --> 00:26:54.740
from the financial
crisis that actually

00:26:54.740 --> 00:26:58.340
may be at least as relevant as
from that early tech bubble.

00:26:58.340 --> 00:27:00.510
MARY GROVE: Think about
