00:30:35.910 --> 00:30:38.049
AUDIENCE: I was
really curious if you

00:30:38.049 --> 00:30:40.090
could talk a little bit
more about the difference

00:30:40.090 --> 00:30:43.160
between a company and a product,
and maybe give some examples

00:30:43.160 --> 00:30:46.600
or features of both.

00:30:46.600 --> 00:30:48.260
RUTH PORAT: Great question.

00:30:48.260 --> 00:30:52.080
So without naming
names, there were

00:30:52.080 --> 00:30:56.510
a number of large
companies in the '90s who

00:30:56.510 --> 00:30:59.759
felt that if they took their
dot-com business public-- think

00:30:59.759 --> 00:31:01.800
of any of the consumer
products goods companies--

00:31:01.800 --> 00:31:03.870
they took their dot-com
business public,

00:31:03.870 --> 00:31:06.490
it would go for some
super high valuation.

00:31:06.490 --> 00:31:09.140
And my point-- that's
a simple example of,

00:31:09.140 --> 00:31:10.710
that's just a
distribution channel no

00:31:10.710 --> 00:31:12.060
different than a catalog.

00:31:12.060 --> 00:31:14.380
So what are you doing that's
actually transformative?

00:31:14.380 --> 00:31:17.040
Amazon did something
that was fundamentally

00:31:17.040 --> 00:31:19.510
transformative in the
experience that you had.

00:31:19.510 --> 00:31:22.390
They weren't doing much
that was differentiated.

00:31:22.390 --> 00:31:24.679
eBay did something,
created a whole new market.

00:31:24.679 --> 00:31:26.220
Priceline created
a whole new market,

00:31:26.220 --> 00:31:30.011
a whole new way of thinking
about how you could consume,

00:31:30.011 --> 00:31:30.510
acquire.

00:31:30.510 --> 00:31:32.300
So for example, I
took Priceline public.

00:31:32.300 --> 00:31:35.070
And what was fascinating
to me was it started

00:31:35.070 --> 00:31:37.960
as just this narrow vertical.

00:31:37.960 --> 00:31:40.630
But they could connect
the dots to the future.

00:31:40.630 --> 00:31:43.630
What more could you do once
you've kind of gone down

00:31:43.630 --> 00:31:44.220
this path?

00:31:44.220 --> 00:31:51.350
And that's probably
one part of it.

00:31:51.350 --> 00:31:53.990
The other is, if the problem
you're solving is too small,

00:31:53.990 --> 00:31:58.550
so it's a nice feature, it's a
nice add-on to an experience,

00:31:58.550 --> 00:32:00.505
the question is, how big
does it really scale?

00:32:00.505 --> 00:32:02.880
So when you start by saying,
what's the total addressable

00:32:02.880 --> 00:32:03.210
market?

00:32:03.210 --> 00:32:04.530
How big could this really be?

00:32:04.530 --> 00:32:08.410
If it's too narrow, then you
end up saying, that's cool.

00:32:08.410 --> 00:32:11.750
That's a nice, cool company.

00:32:11.750 --> 00:32:14.190
But fundamentally, it
would have more reach

00:32:14.190 --> 00:32:16.700
if it plugged into
something broader.

00:32:16.700 --> 00:32:19.015
So it just solves a
slice of a problem.

00:32:21.750 --> 00:32:23.914
MARY GROVE: Yellow microphone.

00:32:23.914 --> 00:32:25.330
AUDIENCE: So my
name is [? Snow ?]

00:32:25.330 --> 00:32:29.310
and I'm an Android developer
at Groupon right now.

00:32:29.310 --> 00:32:30.910
I have two questions for you.

00:32:30.910 --> 00:32:34.310
The first, you said you
have a list of priorities

00:32:34.310 --> 00:32:37.200
for both your work and family.

00:32:37.200 --> 00:32:42.300
Could you share with us, at
least, maybe top one of each?

00:32:42.300 --> 00:32:46.700
And the second thing is,
you have a really busy life

00:32:46.700 --> 00:32:47.470
at work, right?

00:32:47.470 --> 00:32:52.520
Like how do you manage to kind
of balance your personal life?

00:32:52.520 --> 00:32:55.520
Like how do you find
your love of life,

00:32:55.520 --> 00:33:01.860
and then how do you manage your
family time, things like that?

00:33:01.860 --> 00:33:04.900
RUTH PORAT: I'm glad you
asked that because the word

00:33:04.900 --> 00:33:07.780
balance, I think, is one
thing I would love everyone

00:33:07.780 --> 00:33:09.550
in this room to get rid of.

00:33:09.550 --> 00:33:11.130
Banish from your vocabulary.

00:33:11.130 --> 00:33:14.350
I think the term balance,
which is often used,

00:33:14.350 --> 00:33:17.360
is a trap, because we
can never be balanced.

00:33:17.360 --> 00:33:22.630
I think-- my view is
that too often-- I'll

00:33:22.630 --> 00:33:24.614
say for myself-- I feel
guilty all the time

00:33:24.614 --> 00:33:26.280
that I'm not doing
enough for my family,

00:33:26.280 --> 00:33:27.800
or I'm not doing
enough for work.

00:33:27.800 --> 00:33:33.460
And I think women often do feel
very guilty, get that sense of,

00:33:33.460 --> 00:33:35.020
I should be doing more here.

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:36.280
Men don't do it as much.

00:33:36.280 --> 00:33:42.625
Men do a great job of just kind
of compartmentalizing things.

00:33:42.625 --> 00:33:44.750
And there are a lot of
lessons that come from that.

00:33:44.750 --> 00:33:47.990
But sticking with your question,
I don't view it as balance.

00:33:47.990 --> 00:33:48.860
I view it as mix.

00:33:48.860 --> 00:33:52.310
My view is that at
different times in life,

00:33:52.310 --> 00:33:54.840
you're kind of more
one or more the other.

00:33:54.840 --> 00:33:56.800
And the metaphor--
I like to think

00:33:56.800 --> 00:34:00.410
in metaphors-- but the metaphor
for me is a kaleidoscope.

00:34:00.410 --> 00:34:02.967
If the kaleidoscope had
half yellow and half blue,

00:34:02.967 --> 00:34:04.050
it would be pretty boring.

00:34:04.050 --> 00:34:06.466
If it had all yellow and all
blue, it would be even worse.

00:34:06.466 --> 00:34:08.449
But even if it was
just perfectly equal,

00:34:08.449 --> 00:34:10.090
nicely balanced.

00:34:10.090 --> 00:34:12.330
Instead, it's a lot
of different colors.

00:34:12.330 --> 00:34:14.800
And as you move throughout
life, it changes,

00:34:14.800 --> 00:34:17.090
and that's what makes
it really beautiful.

00:34:17.090 --> 00:34:19.230
And I was really fortunate.

00:34:19.230 --> 00:34:21.290
My mom worked when I was
growing up and always

00:34:21.290 --> 00:34:22.940
gave me the message
that I should work.

00:34:22.940 --> 00:34:25.584
And I love my mom
immensely, and I'm

00:34:25.584 --> 00:34:26.750
really close to my siblings.

00:34:26.750 --> 00:34:30.150
So it never occurred to me that
you couldn't be a great mom

00:34:30.150 --> 00:34:31.409
and have a great career.

00:34:31.409 --> 00:34:33.510
And my dad was
completely gender blind

00:34:33.510 --> 00:34:38.030
and did math problems
and soldering circuitry

00:34:38.030 --> 00:34:39.320
and really cool stuff with me.

00:34:39.320 --> 00:34:42.380
So I was never
told anything other

00:34:42.380 --> 00:34:44.739
than go forth and be
what you want to be.

00:34:44.739 --> 00:34:47.810
And when I was little,
my kids-- it was hard.

00:34:47.810 --> 00:34:50.699
I mean, there's no question,
when you're going to work,

00:34:50.699 --> 00:34:52.159
you have those bad days.

00:34:52.159 --> 00:34:57.280
I was reminiscing about my
middle kid when he was little.

00:34:57.280 --> 00:34:59.690
They're now all in their 20s.

00:34:59.690 --> 00:35:01.670
But when he was
little, one day he

00:35:01.670 --> 00:35:03.130
said, mommy, why do you work?

00:35:03.130 --> 00:35:07.550
And I thought, what a great
time for a learning moment.

00:35:07.550 --> 00:35:10.760
I work because I
love to help clients

00:35:10.760 --> 00:35:12.280
and I love to solve
their problems.

00:35:12.280 --> 00:35:14.610
And I work with
really fun people.

00:35:14.610 --> 00:35:16.540
And he reflected
on it and he said,

00:35:16.540 --> 00:35:18.670
so mommy, it comes down
to that one word, love.

00:35:18.670 --> 00:35:20.210
Who do you love more?

00:35:20.210 --> 00:35:22.840
Which was clearly
not the response

00:35:22.840 --> 00:35:24.830
that I was looking for.

00:35:24.830 --> 00:35:27.470
But if you fast
forward to when we

00:35:27.470 --> 00:35:30.080
were going through the
financial crisis, they got it.

00:35:30.080 --> 00:35:32.456
They knew that I was in the
middle of something that

00:35:32.456 --> 00:35:33.330
was really important.

00:35:33.330 --> 00:35:36.860
They were so there and they were
proud, and they really got it.

00:35:36.860 --> 00:35:39.330
And we're super close.

00:35:39.330 --> 00:35:42.680
And I think that
my husband and I

00:35:42.680 --> 00:35:46.060
have launched three boys,
three, I guess, young men now

00:35:46.060 --> 00:35:47.470
who have really good values.

00:35:47.470 --> 00:35:48.170
They get it.

00:35:48.170 --> 00:35:52.470
They see how wonderful
it is to have all of us

00:35:52.470 --> 00:35:53.740
be who we can be.

00:35:53.740 --> 00:35:57.410
So for me, this term balance--
the reason I jumped on it,

00:35:57.410 --> 00:36:01.150
I'm glad you used it-- is
because I think it's a trap.

00:36:01.150 --> 00:36:04.310
Think about mix, and
it adjusts over time.

00:36:04.310 --> 00:36:05.960
And one of the very
important things

00:36:05.960 --> 00:36:08.640
I think, as leaders,
we should all do,

00:36:08.640 --> 00:36:11.580
is help women deal
with that guilt,

00:36:11.580 --> 00:36:16.800
because-- what I have
set up in my prior role,

00:36:16.800 --> 00:36:18.956
and I certainly have it
here-- is I tell women,

00:36:18.956 --> 00:36:21.080
you know what, if there's
something you want to do,

00:36:21.080 --> 00:36:24.770
like whatever with the family,
a kid's birthday, a parent

00:36:24.770 --> 00:36:27.800
teacher conference, a sporting
event, whatever, don't tell me.

00:36:27.800 --> 00:36:29.340
Just go do it,
because I trust you.

00:36:29.340 --> 00:36:30.923
You're on my team
because I trust you.

00:36:30.923 --> 00:36:31.890
Don't check in with me.

00:36:31.890 --> 00:36:34.170
Women tend to check
in more often.

00:36:34.170 --> 00:36:36.670
Men just go do what
they need to do.

00:36:36.670 --> 00:36:40.480
And so what I've told men is
you need to let everyone know,

00:36:40.480 --> 00:36:42.290
don't check in with me.

00:36:42.290 --> 00:36:43.990
Go do what you need
to do, and view it

00:36:43.990 --> 00:36:47.380
as an investment in your
longevity at Alphabet,

00:36:47.380 --> 00:36:50.410
at Morgan Stanley, at
wherever you happen to work.

00:36:50.410 --> 00:36:54.640
And over the years I've had
women send me a note saying,

00:36:54.640 --> 00:36:57.000
I know I wasn't supposed
to check in with my boss,

00:36:57.000 --> 00:36:59.480
but I've never done that so
I'm sending you an email just

00:36:59.480 --> 00:37:02.270
to tell you that's really cool
advice but it's still hard.

00:37:02.270 --> 00:37:02.980
And I love it.

00:37:02.980 --> 00:37:04.521
I mean, it's like,
yeah, bring it on.

00:37:04.521 --> 00:37:05.100
It's fine.

00:37:05.100 --> 00:37:07.605
Because it does feel a bit
odd if you're not there

00:37:07.605 --> 00:37:09.230
or you're cutting
out in the afternoon.

00:37:09.230 --> 00:37:10.580
But the guys do it.

00:37:10.580 --> 00:37:12.430
So feel good about
it, and view it

00:37:12.430 --> 00:37:15.330
as an investment in the
longevity of your time

00:37:15.330 --> 00:37:17.200
at wherever it is
you're working.

00:37:17.200 --> 00:37:19.060
I think it's really important.

00:37:19.060 --> 00:37:21.010
MARY GROVE: Thank you, Ruth.

00:37:21.010 --> 00:37:22.097
Next question.

00:37:22.097 --> 00:37:22.680
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:37:22.680 --> 00:37:25.000
My name is [? Mina ?]
[? Kasi. ?] And

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:29.000
I'm at the point of my career
where I'm transitioning from

00:37:29.000 --> 00:37:31.780
an individual contributor
to management role.

00:37:31.780 --> 00:37:35.880
So along that path, as you
said, you had several sponsors.

00:37:35.880 --> 00:37:40.090
But at the same time, I'm
being viewed as a threat

00:37:40.090 --> 00:37:43.920
to other colleagues
competing for the same.

00:37:43.920 --> 00:37:46.830
Because you have gone
up the ladder so much

00:37:46.830 --> 00:37:49.500
and you always had
sponsors, how did you

00:37:49.500 --> 00:37:52.200
deal with any oppositions?

00:37:52.200 --> 00:37:57.950
Or what was your way
around that problem?

00:37:57.950 --> 00:38:00.550
RUTH PORAT: Well, I think when
you're picked versus a guy,

00:38:00.550 --> 00:38:03.210
or when two guys are up for
a role, and one gets picked

00:38:03.210 --> 00:38:05.520
and the other doesn't,
there's obviously

00:38:05.520 --> 00:38:08.450
disappointment and envy
and a whole host of things.

00:38:08.450 --> 00:38:13.250
I think that all we can do is
conduct ourselves as ethically

00:38:13.250 --> 00:38:15.120
and responsibly as possible.

00:38:15.120 --> 00:38:16.770
I can't deal with their problem.

00:38:16.770 --> 00:38:17.740
Like you know what?

00:38:17.740 --> 00:38:21.240
If you're the one who should
get picked for the role,

00:38:21.240 --> 00:38:22.710
do it in a high-quality way.

00:38:22.710 --> 00:38:25.040
Make sure you're super
inclusive of your team.

00:38:25.040 --> 00:38:27.770
I think one of the
great things in leaders

00:38:27.770 --> 00:38:31.460
is, when you're a leader, one,
over-communicate with the team.

00:38:31.460 --> 00:38:33.310
Make sure they know
what your vision is.

00:38:33.310 --> 00:38:37.160
And when you're in a room, make
sure you get everybody's views

00:38:37.160 --> 00:38:39.350
before you opine on yours.

00:38:39.350 --> 00:38:42.460
If you've got the support of
your team, those snipers who

00:38:42.460 --> 00:38:44.542
wish they had the role
but didn't get it,

00:38:44.542 --> 00:38:47.000
they're not going to get much
support for it because you're

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:48.350
going to be doing a great job.

00:38:48.350 --> 00:38:51.400
So there have been
times in my career--

00:38:51.400 --> 00:38:55.129
I came from an industry where
there were even fewer women.

00:38:55.129 --> 00:38:56.670
It was tougher in
those earlier years

00:38:56.670 --> 00:38:58.250
than, I would say,
in this industry.

00:38:58.250 --> 00:39:01.240
And fortunately all of these
industries are changing.

00:39:01.240 --> 00:39:04.084
There were times when I tried
to even use to my advantage,

00:39:04.084 --> 00:39:06.250
well, you know, I'm a woman,
so they wanted a woman.

00:39:06.250 --> 00:39:07.920
I'm not sure that's
the best answer,

00:39:07.920 --> 00:39:09.980
and I certainly am not
going to say I advocate.

00:39:09.980 --> 00:39:11.820
In fact, I'm even
sorry I brought it up.

00:39:11.820 --> 00:39:13.140
But you know what?

00:39:13.140 --> 00:39:15.620
We can't deal with
the guys' problems.

00:39:15.620 --> 00:39:18.050
And we're just going
to move forward.

00:39:20.630 --> 00:39:22.820
MARY GROVE: Yes, question
in the green microphone.

00:39:22.820 --> 00:39:26.612
AUDIENCE: Hey, my name is
[? Rosha. ?] I work at Udacity.

00:39:26.612 --> 00:39:28.600
Hey.

00:39:28.600 --> 00:39:32.090
So my question is, what
personality traits and skills

00:39:32.090 --> 00:39:34.430
you look for in a person
that would get you to say,

00:39:34.430 --> 00:39:36.780
I want to sponsor that
person, and I want

00:39:36.780 --> 00:39:39.135
to contribute to their success?

00:39:39.135 --> 00:39:41.260
MARY GROVE: [? Rosha ?] is
an amazing entrepreneur.

00:39:41.260 --> 00:39:43.343
We first met in Palestine,
and she lives here now.

00:39:43.343 --> 00:39:46.240
RUTH PORAT: Oh, cool.

00:39:46.240 --> 00:39:50.520
It kind of goes
back to my comments.

00:39:50.520 --> 00:39:54.550
I want someone who
is challenging,

00:39:54.550 --> 00:39:57.790
who's in my face with ideas.

00:39:57.790 --> 00:40:04.120
One of my favorite analysts
who worked for me-- actually,

00:40:04.120 --> 00:40:07.910
he's now here, came
here years before I did.

00:40:07.910 --> 00:40:09.780
Very wise guy, clearly.

00:40:09.780 --> 00:40:11.530
But you know, what
I really liked was,

00:40:11.530 --> 00:40:14.420
he was a very young kid
right out of college

00:40:14.420 --> 00:40:15.670
and I was a managing director.

00:40:15.670 --> 00:40:18.080
And he was constantly
peppering me with ideas,

00:40:18.080 --> 00:40:21.010
because as I said, none of
us have a monopoly on ideas.

00:40:21.010 --> 00:40:24.560
So I want people who give
me real operating leverage

00:40:24.560 --> 00:40:27.290
by provoking great ideas.

00:40:27.290 --> 00:40:32.620
And I've often used the term
"think, don't process," which

00:40:32.620 --> 00:40:35.540
is a really crass
way of describing it,

00:40:35.540 --> 00:40:37.710
because I don't think
any of us just process.

00:40:37.710 --> 00:40:41.090
But if you don't complete what
you're trying to do and then go

00:40:41.090 --> 00:40:44.630
the next level, so put yourself
in the more senior person's

00:40:44.630 --> 00:40:48.410
position and say, what
would I do if I were there?

00:40:48.410 --> 00:40:49.900
So this tells me a story.

00:40:49.900 --> 00:40:50.840
What's the next step?

00:40:50.840 --> 00:40:54.572
Try and take it the next
step or the step beyond that.

00:40:54.572 --> 00:40:57.030
Once you're doing that, you're
providing a ton of operating

00:40:57.030 --> 00:40:57.890
leverage to people.

00:40:57.890 --> 00:41:00.760
So the eureka
moment for me was, I

00:41:00.760 --> 00:41:03.210
was so grateful to my
sponsors-- and I am.

00:41:03.210 --> 00:41:05.590
I wouldn't have had these
roles but for sponsors--

00:41:05.590 --> 00:41:07.110
until one day I
realized, I think

00:41:07.110 --> 00:41:09.200
that guy's getting at
least as much out of me

00:41:09.200 --> 00:41:10.880
as I am out of
this relationship.

00:41:10.880 --> 00:41:13.520
It's a really fair relationship.

00:41:13.520 --> 00:41:15.910
And that's when you
realize that it's working.

00:41:15.910 --> 00:41:18.370
So when you're
sponsoring someone,

00:41:18.370 --> 00:41:21.190
I've got a ton of
people, and it's probably

00:41:21.190 --> 00:41:22.830
the most gratifying
part of my role,

00:41:22.830 --> 00:41:24.780
is people who keep
updating me from wherever

00:41:24.780 --> 00:41:27.745
they are in life who I've worked
with over the last 20 years.

00:41:27.745 --> 00:41:29.910
And it's because
they've got this spark

00:41:29.910 --> 00:41:32.170
and they're trying to
push it to the next level.

00:41:32.170 --> 00:41:38.010
And even people who come to
me-- for example, one guy,

00:41:38.010 --> 00:41:39.860
he kept coming up with ideas.

00:41:39.860 --> 00:41:41.760
And I said to him,
I love the way

00:41:41.760 --> 00:41:43.740
you think but your
ideas are too small.

00:41:43.740 --> 00:41:44.860
Think bigger.

00:41:44.860 --> 00:41:48.060
And so you just want to
provoke people to think,

00:41:48.060 --> 00:41:51.560
because if you can get them
to understand how big you want

00:41:51.560 --> 00:41:54.110
to think, or which markets
you want to attack,

00:41:54.110 --> 00:41:57.300
they may miss the mark because
they're new at doing it,

00:41:57.300 --> 00:41:59.810
but you can redirect them.

00:41:59.810 --> 00:42:01.220
That's what I look for.

00:42:01.220 --> 00:42:03.140
And so it is this challenge.

00:42:03.140 --> 00:42:05.627
I want people who
are challenging.

00:42:05.627 --> 00:42:07.960
MARY GROVE: We have time for
one final audience question

00:42:07.960 --> 00:42:10.130
in the purple microphone.

00:42:10.130 --> 00:42:13.550
AUDIENCE: So I wanted to get
your opinion of, or ideas,

00:42:13.550 --> 00:42:17.780
on that if you are somebody
who's working full-time

00:42:17.780 --> 00:42:20.510
as a software developer,
how do you transition?

00:42:20.510 --> 00:42:23.980
How do you plan from
working from someone

00:42:23.980 --> 00:42:27.840
to having something of your
own, your own software service,

00:42:27.840 --> 00:42:31.770
given the assumptions
that you have

00:42:31.770 --> 00:42:34.290
to plan all the
financial aspect of it,

00:42:34.290 --> 00:42:37.110
or you don't have a network.

00:42:37.110 --> 00:42:40.180
You can take the knowledge
of a guy in a garage,

00:42:40.180 --> 00:42:42.620
but we don't see a lot of
women in the garage creating

00:42:42.620 --> 00:42:43.570
something.

00:42:43.570 --> 00:42:47.390
So what's your thoughts on it?

00:42:47.390 --> 00:42:49.880
RUTH PORAT: Well, you may have,
given your role, a lot more

00:42:49.880 --> 00:42:51.130
to add on this than I do.

00:42:51.130 --> 00:42:53.590
I mean, I keep coming
back to the same playbook

00:42:53.590 --> 00:42:57.270
in certain respects,
which is, you

00:42:57.270 --> 00:43:01.100
do need to be able
to address what's

00:43:01.100 --> 00:43:03.840
the technical model, what's
the business model, what's

00:43:03.840 --> 00:43:06.800
the financial model,
what's the marketing model?

00:43:06.800 --> 00:43:09.400
Just one piece of the
puzzle doesn't solve it.

00:43:09.400 --> 00:43:12.420
So whether you bring in
people who can do it,

00:43:12.420 --> 00:43:14.560
I think life is a team sport.

00:43:14.560 --> 00:43:18.510
And I want to make sure that
I'm surrounded with people who

00:43:18.510 --> 00:43:20.060
are part of that team sport.

00:43:20.060 --> 00:43:24.470
And so I would make sure to
fill in what those gaps are.

00:43:24.470 --> 00:43:26.520
And there's a pretty
big network of people,

00:43:26.520 --> 00:43:28.450
in particular, I
think, who want to see

00:43:28.450 --> 00:43:31.960
more women thriving and
rising up and really winning.

00:43:31.960 --> 00:43:34.450
And that's a great place to be.

00:43:34.450 --> 00:43:35.944
MARY GROVE: I would say test.

00:43:35.944 --> 00:43:37.610
Test the concept early
and often, right?

00:43:37.610 --> 00:43:40.142
Put your ideas out there
with trusted people

00:43:40.142 --> 00:43:42.600
across different disciplines,
whether it's product, design,

00:43:42.600 --> 00:43:44.520
engineering, the business side.

00:43:44.520 --> 00:43:46.700
There are amazing forums
like startup weekends,

00:43:46.700 --> 00:43:49.360
these small boot camps where
you can go and actually

00:43:49.360 --> 00:43:52.324
work on it in a mock scenario,
get real life feedback.

00:43:52.324 --> 00:43:53.740
And the third thing
is, maybe talk

00:43:53.740 --> 00:43:56.220
with some potential angel
investors, friends and family,

00:43:56.220 --> 00:43:58.351
folks who have seen a lot
of these different types

00:43:58.351 --> 00:43:59.350
of pitches come through.

00:43:59.350 --> 00:44:01.058
And they may have a
lot of great feedback

00:44:01.058 --> 00:44:03.687
early on before you end
up taking that leap.

00:44:03.687 --> 00:44:05.770
RUTH PORAT: I just want
to say it's fabulous being

00:44:05.770 --> 00:44:06.380
with all of you.

00:44:06.380 --> 00:44:07.504
What you're doing is great.

00:44:07.504 --> 00:44:09.720
We need to see more
women continuing

00:44:09.720 --> 00:44:11.100
to thrive in this industry.

00:44:11.100 --> 00:44:13.690
And it's a thrill and pleasure
to be with all of you.

00:44:13.690 --> 00:44:15.100
So congratulations
to all of you.

00:44:15.100 --> 00:44:16.660
MARY GROVE: And on
that note, Ruth,

00:44:16.660 --> 00:44:19.240
I want to ask you a
couple-- if I may.

00:44:19.240 --> 00:44:19.865
RUTH PORAT: Oh.

00:44:19.865 --> 00:44:21.031
MARY GROVE: I like to close.

00:44:21.031 --> 00:44:23.090
RUTH PORAT: I thought we
had one last question.

00:44:23.090 --> 00:44:25.970
MARY GROVE: Well, I get to
sneak a couple in there.

00:44:25.970 --> 00:44:29.200
So I wanted to ask you
to do a small game I

00:44:29.200 --> 00:44:30.590
have called Fill in the Blank.

00:44:30.590 --> 00:44:31.720
So I'm just going to give you--

00:44:31.720 --> 00:44:32.520
RUTH PORAT: Mad Libs.

00:44:32.520 --> 00:44:33.395
We're doing Mad Libs.

00:44:33.395 --> 00:44:34.561
MARY GROVE: Brief statement.

00:44:34.561 --> 00:44:36.740
Give me the first word or
phrase that comes to mind.

00:44:36.740 --> 00:44:37.710
RUTH PORAT: OK.

00:44:37.710 --> 00:44:39.740
MARY GROVE: So if I
started the company today,

00:44:39.740 --> 00:44:43.170
it would be focused on--

00:44:43.170 --> 00:44:44.900
RUTH PORAT: So can
I violate the rule?

00:44:47.197 --> 00:44:49.030
MARY GROVE: Don't ask
for permission, right?

00:44:49.030 --> 00:44:50.238
RUTH PORAT: Oh yeah, exactly.

00:44:52.790 --> 00:44:54.420
My mom was an entrepreneur.

00:44:54.420 --> 00:44:57.600
And I have so much
respect for entrepreneurs.

00:44:57.600 --> 00:44:59.490
And I think people
who are entrepreneurs

00:44:59.490 --> 00:45:01.910
should go off, and
break down those walls,

00:45:01.910 --> 00:45:04.010
and build these great
ideas, and bring

00:45:04.010 --> 00:45:05.850
in whatever you need to do it.

00:45:05.850 --> 00:45:08.020
I love my role,
and I'm not going

00:45:08.020 --> 00:45:11.930
to go be another role
because I love what I do.

00:45:11.930 --> 00:45:15.130
And I feel like the
opportunity to be

00:45:15.130 --> 00:45:18.490
a part of this great
company, making

00:45:18.490 --> 00:45:20.170
sure we've got that
great foundation,

00:45:20.170 --> 00:45:22.570
making sure that mud
is off the windshield,

00:45:22.570 --> 00:45:25.535
solving whatever capital
structure, business capital

00:45:25.535 --> 00:45:27.580
allocation, I love
that part of it.

00:45:27.580 --> 00:45:29.420
And I love the fact
that I work with people

00:45:29.420 --> 00:45:32.220
who are amazing engineers
and entrepreneurs.

00:45:32.220 --> 00:45:34.100
And I think the most
important thing is

00:45:34.100 --> 00:45:36.160
to be super true to yourself.

00:45:36.160 --> 00:45:41.240
And so that's my one-word
answer to your question.

00:45:41.240 --> 00:45:44.430
MARY GROVE: So
leadership to me means--

00:45:44.430 --> 00:45:48.060
RUTH PORAT: Leadership means
courage, because by the time

00:45:48.060 --> 00:45:50.640
it gets to your office,
it's not an easy--

00:45:50.640 --> 00:45:52.500
you never get the easy things.

00:45:52.500 --> 00:45:54.490
But you better make a
decision, because there's

00:45:54.490 --> 00:45:57.720
nothing worse than things
just sort of dragging on.

00:45:57.720 --> 00:46:00.890
It means being really inclusive.

00:46:00.890 --> 00:46:04.060
As I said, I think pulling
the best ideas out,

00:46:04.060 --> 00:46:06.372
that's what great leaders do.

00:46:06.372 --> 00:46:07.830
And it's knowing
where you're going

00:46:07.830 --> 00:46:10.900
with clarity, which often comes
from that process of pulling

00:46:10.900 --> 00:46:11.900
things out.

00:46:11.900 --> 00:46:15.270
MARY GROVE: My final one is,
my hope for the next generation

00:46:15.270 --> 00:46:17.780
of female leaders is--

00:46:17.780 --> 00:46:20.170
RUTH PORAT: Everything
that we all want it to be.

00:46:20.170 --> 00:46:24.860
I think that the pendulum
has moved a lot from when

00:46:24.860 --> 00:46:26.670
my mom was working.

00:46:26.670 --> 00:46:30.810
And it's certainly moved
a lot from when I started.

00:46:30.810 --> 00:46:33.060
And there's such a
great network of women

00:46:33.060 --> 00:46:36.850
that want to see all of
you, and the next generation

00:46:36.850 --> 00:46:40.570
coming up, not asking
these questions about,

00:46:40.570 --> 00:46:42.820
what does it mean
as a woman versus--

00:46:42.820 --> 00:46:45.324
just that it's so natural and
seamless and everything else.

00:46:45.324 --> 00:46:47.240
And until that time,
we're all locked in arms,

00:46:47.240 --> 00:46:48.850
I think, in a really
important way.

00:46:48.850 --> 00:46:52.210
So I want huge
success, and I want

00:46:52.210 --> 00:46:54.200
us to be running the
world because we're

00:46:54.200 --> 00:46:55.495
better at it than anyone else.

00:46:55.495 --> 00:46:56.132
How's that?

00:46:56.132 --> 00:46:57.965
MARY GROVE: Thank you
very much, Ruth Porat.

00:46:57.965 --> 00:46:58.465
[APPLAUSE]

00:46:58.465 --> 00:47:01.190
RUTH PORAT: Thank you.

